Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eccles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Eccles in Lancashire, or possibly from any of several other places so named in Kent, Norfolk, Berwickshire, and Dumfriesshire, from British <i>eglēs</i> ‘Romano-British Christian church’ (from Latin <i>ecclesia</i>, Greek <i>ekklēsia</i> ‘gathering, assembly’). Such places would have been the sites of notable pre-Anglo-Saxon churches or Christian places of communal worship."],"variants":[{"name":"Ackles","meanings":["Altered form of English   Eccles  ."]},{"name":"Exley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from Exley in Southowram (Yorkshire), from British <i>eglēs</i> ‘Romano-British Christian church’ (from Latin <i>ecclesia</i>, Greek <i>ekklēsia</i> ‘gathering, assembly’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Eccles  .","Americanized form of South German   Oechsle  ."]},{"name":"Echols","meanings":["Altered form of English   Eccles   and possibly also of German   Eckels  ."]},{"name":"Eckles","meanings":["English: variant of   Eccles  . This form is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William De Eccles was born about 1255, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Adam Mac warin De Eccles. He had at least 1 son. He died before 1325, in Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1255–before 1325":"umbes 1255–enne 1325","1255–1325":"1255–1325","1255–1329":"1255–1329","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","before 1325":"enne 1325","1325":"1325","1255":"1255","about 1255":"umbes 1255","1150":"1150","1329":"1329","Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1255–before 1325":"noin 1255–ennen vuotta 1325","1255–1325":"1255–1325","1255–1329":"1255–1329","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","before 1325":"ennen vuotta 1325","1325":"1325","1255":"1255","about 1255":"noin 1255","1150":"1150","1329":"1329","Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1255–before 1325":"environ 1255–avant 1325","1255–1325":"1255–1325","1255–1329":"1255–1329","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","before 1325":"avant 1325","1325":"1325","1255":"1255","about 1255":"environ 1255","1150":"1150","1329":"1329","Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kildonan, Inverness-shire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Écosse, R